meta {
  name: Test Dangerous Headers
  type: http
  seq: 13
}

get {
  url: http://localhost:30080/example-api/
  body: none
  auth: none
}

headers {
  X-Forwarded-Host: evil.com
  X-Original-URL: /admin
  X-HTTP-Method-Override: DELETE
  X-Debug: true
}

docs {
  # Test Header Sanitization (WAF)

  Sends a request with dangerous headers that should be stripped by the WAF.
  When Header Sanitization is enabled, the gateway will:
  - **Strip** dangerous headers (X-Forwarded-Host, X-Original-URL, etc.) before proxying
  - **Log** the sanitization event in the WAF event log

  ## Prerequisites
  1. Deploy a service (e.g., "example-api")
  2. Go to the service's **Firewall** tab in the UI
  3. Turn ON the **Header Sanitization** toggle

  ## Expected Behavior
  - The request **passes through** (200 OK) but dangerous headers are stripped
  - A "Headers" event appears in the WAF event log showing which headers were removed
  - The downstream service never sees the dangerous headers

  ## Dangerous headers being sent
  - `X-Forwarded-Host: evil.com` — Host header injection / cache poisoning
  - `X-Original-URL: /admin` — URL rewrite / SSRF attack
  - `X-HTTP-Method-Override: DELETE` — Method override attack
  - `X-Debug: true` — Debug header leak
}
